WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.630
CHRISTINE BREINER: Welcome
back to recitation.

00:00:08.630 --> 00:00:10.650
I want us to work a little
more on finding

00:00:10.650 --> 00:00:11.540
anti-derivatives.

00:00:11.540 --> 00:00:13.830
In particular, in this video
we want to find an

00:00:13.830 --> 00:00:17.900
anti-derivative of a
trigonometric function, a

00:00:17.900 --> 00:00:20.500
power of the tangent function.

00:00:20.500 --> 00:00:24.880
So I would like you to find an
anti-derivative of tangent

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:26.840
theta quantity to the fourth.

00:00:26.840 --> 00:00:30.650
And the hint I will give you is
that you're going to need

00:00:30.650 --> 00:00:33.780
some fairly familiar,
hopefully, by now,

00:00:33.780 --> 00:00:36.550
trigonometric identities
to get this to work.

00:00:36.550 --> 00:00:38.600
And then you will need some
other strategies that you've

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:39.970
also been developing.

00:00:39.970 --> 00:00:42.150
So I'll give you a while to work
on it and then I'll be

00:00:42.150 --> 00:00:43.410
back and I'll show
you how I did it.

00:00:52.150 --> 00:00:52.490
OK.

00:00:52.490 --> 00:00:53.450
Welcome back.

00:00:53.450 --> 00:00:56.690
We want to, again, we want to
find an anti-derivative for

00:00:56.690 --> 00:00:58.870
tangent theta quantity
to the fourth.

00:00:58.870 --> 00:01:01.810
And I mentioned that what
we're going to need is a

00:01:01.810 --> 00:01:02.850
particular trigonometric--

00:01:02.850 --> 00:01:05.210
well, I didn't say particular,
sorry-- but we will need some

00:01:05.210 --> 00:01:07.600
trigonometric identities
to make this work.

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:10.160
And the one in particular I'll
be exploiting is a certain

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:15.010
one, which I'll write down here,
which is, 1 plus tangent

00:01:15.010 --> 00:01:18.550
squared theta is equal to
secant squared theta.

00:01:18.550 --> 00:01:21.430
We've seen that, I think, a fair
amount now, but just to

00:01:21.430 --> 00:01:24.400
remind ourselves, it is
important, and this is the one

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:26.420
we're going to use.

00:01:26.420 --> 00:01:29.440
So let me show you how this
works, how this identity will

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:31.010
be very useful in here.

00:01:31.010 --> 00:01:33.550
And the idea is that we can
break up this tangent to the

00:01:33.550 --> 00:01:37.180
fourth theta into two,
the product of two

00:01:37.180 --> 00:01:38.720
tangent squared thetas.

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:42.570
So I can rewrite this integral
above as the integral of

00:01:42.570 --> 00:01:46.380
tangent squared theta times
another tangent squared theta.

00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:48.810
But instead of that, I'm going
to use this identity.

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:51.120
So I'm going to write
it as secant squared

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:53.810
theta minus 1 d theta.

00:01:53.810 --> 00:01:56.870
So just let me make sure
everybody follows what I did.

00:01:56.870 --> 00:02:01.100
I had tangent to the fourth
theta as my initial integral,

00:02:01.100 --> 00:02:04.690
so then I wrote it as tangent
squared times tangent squared.

00:02:04.690 --> 00:02:06.990
And this is actually equal
to tangent squared.

00:02:06.990 --> 00:02:09.250
You notice I just subtracted
1 from both sides

00:02:09.250 --> 00:02:11.870
of the starred identity.

00:02:11.870 --> 00:02:13.170
So that's my other
tangent squared.

00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:15.830
So these two integrals
are actually equal.

00:02:15.830 --> 00:02:17.630
So I haven't changed anything
fundamentally

00:02:17.630 --> 00:02:19.350
at all in the problem.

00:02:19.350 --> 00:02:19.520
All right.

00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:22.300
Now let's look at what
we get here.

00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:25.130
We get, if I distribute this,
I get integral tan squared

00:02:25.130 --> 00:02:32.200
theta secant squared theta d
theta minus the integral of

00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:36.380
tan squared theta d theta.

00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:40.485
Now, you should start to see
that maybe even powers of

00:02:40.485 --> 00:02:41.900
tangent theta are nice
to deal with.

00:02:41.900 --> 00:02:44.865
Because this kind of stuff is
going to happen, this is going

00:02:44.865 --> 00:02:50.280
to happen every time with, you
know, n minus 2, the power n

00:02:50.280 --> 00:02:53.470
minus 2, here, for any
n I have up here.

00:02:53.470 --> 00:02:55.910
And the reason the even is--

00:02:55.910 --> 00:02:57.780
actually, I guess the even
doesn't even really matter.

00:02:57.780 --> 00:02:59.340
I could just have any n
and this would be n

00:02:59.340 --> 00:03:01.370
minus 2 down here.

00:03:01.370 --> 00:03:04.040
This is an easy integral
to deal with.

00:03:04.040 --> 00:03:05.370
Why is that?

00:03:05.370 --> 00:03:09.150
Because what's the derivative
of the tangent function?

00:03:09.150 --> 00:03:09.955
It's secant squared.

00:03:09.955 --> 00:03:11.080
Right?

00:03:11.080 --> 00:03:14.530
So this is actually a straight
up u-substitution, or

00:03:14.530 --> 00:03:16.080
substitution type problem.

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:19.000
So this, I can finish and I will
later, but this will be

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:20.250
substitution.

00:03:21.980 --> 00:03:23.980
So I'll finish that
in a little bit.

00:03:23.980 --> 00:03:25.720
But what about this?

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:27.520
Now I have tan squared
theta d theta.

00:03:30.970 --> 00:03:31.340
That's, you know, we don't
have any, we don't have a

00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:32.970
secant here.

00:03:32.970 --> 00:03:34.980
We don't have secant squared
here, which would make it

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:36.770
obviously nice-- that's
what we had here.

00:03:36.770 --> 00:03:39.240
So we need to do something
else with this.

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:41.450
Well, what I'm going to do is,
I'm again going to use the

00:03:41.450 --> 00:03:43.320
trigonometric identity.

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:47.960
I'm going to replace this
tangent squares theta by

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:50.760
secant squared theta minus 1.

00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:52.430
Let's think about,
why is that good?

00:03:52.430 --> 00:03:56.170
Well, that's good because what
I end up with is, if I have

00:03:56.170 --> 00:03:58.150
secant squared theta minus 1--

00:03:58.150 --> 00:03:59.600
is what this will equal--

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:01.750
secant squared theta is
easy to integrate.

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:04.040
Because it's the derivative of a
trig function we know-- it's

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:05.860
the derivative of tangent.

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:08.640
And 1, I think, is pretty
easy to integrate, too.

00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:11.960
So we have two functions we
can integrate very easily.

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:15.370
So I'm going to bring this back
up on the next line, I'm

00:04:15.370 --> 00:04:17.570
going to do the replacement
here, and then we'll finish

00:04:17.570 --> 00:04:19.860
the problem.

00:04:19.860 --> 00:04:21.110
So let me write this down.

00:04:28.260 --> 00:04:28.650
OK.

00:04:28.650 --> 00:04:32.460
Now I'm going to do my
replacement and minus the

00:04:32.460 --> 00:04:41.300
quantity the integral secant
squared theta minus 1 d theta.

00:04:41.300 --> 00:04:43.040
Let's make sure I didn't
make any mistakes.

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:46.140
So I had tan squared theta
secant squared theta d theta.

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:47.110
That looks good.

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:50.640
And then I'm subtracting tan
squared theta, the integral of

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:51.270
tan squared theta d theta.

00:04:51.270 --> 00:04:51.980
And that's that.

00:04:51.980 --> 00:04:53.490
So I'm OK.

00:04:53.490 --> 00:04:56.810
So this one, again, I mentioned
that this is going

00:04:56.810 --> 00:04:58.300
to be a substitution.

00:04:58.300 --> 00:05:00.995
If you need to write it out
explicitly, this is u equals

00:05:00.995 --> 00:05:06.650
tan theta, so du is equal to
secant squared theta d theta.

00:05:06.650 --> 00:05:08.015
So this is the integral
of u squared.

00:05:08.015 --> 00:05:09.760
Right?

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:11.715
If I substitute in I
get u squared du.

00:05:11.715 --> 00:05:13.250
So it's the integral of
u squared, which is

00:05:13.250 --> 00:05:15.460
u cubed over 3.

00:05:15.460 --> 00:05:20.880
So that first part is going to
be tan cubed theta over 3.

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:22.690
That's my first term.

00:05:22.690 --> 00:05:24.710
That's a straight up
substitution pretty similar to

00:05:24.710 --> 00:05:26.440
what you've seen.

00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:27.960
Now I have two things
to integrate.

00:05:27.960 --> 00:05:30.520
I have to integrate secant
squared theta, and I have to

00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:31.600
integrate the 1.

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:35.590
Well, derivative of tangent
is secant squared.

00:05:35.590 --> 00:05:37.700
So the integral of secant
squared theta is

00:05:37.700 --> 00:05:39.550
just tangent theta.

00:05:39.550 --> 00:05:41.810
So I have to subtract, so
there's a minus sine of

00:05:41.810 --> 00:05:44.110
tangent theta.

00:05:44.110 --> 00:05:47.750
And then I have a minus, minus,
so when I integrate 1 d

00:05:47.750 --> 00:05:52.740
theta, I'm going to
get a plus theta.

00:05:52.740 --> 00:05:55.680
And then, obviously, because
it's a family of possible

00:05:55.680 --> 00:05:59.170
solutions, I can add a constant
there, plus c.

00:05:59.170 --> 00:06:00.760
So again, where did
these come from?

00:06:00.760 --> 00:06:04.300
This first one was
a u-substitution

00:06:04.300 --> 00:06:06.300
on the first integral.

00:06:06.300 --> 00:06:08.780
And then over here I have
another integral with two

00:06:08.780 --> 00:06:10.200
terms inside.

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:12.760
The first one is just
the, I just need to

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:13.760
integrate secant squared.

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:15.370
I get tangent theta.

00:06:15.370 --> 00:06:18.170
The second one, I just need to
integrate the 1, and so I have

00:06:18.170 --> 00:06:19.020
a negative, negative.

00:06:19.020 --> 00:06:21.160
That makes it a positive
theta.

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:23.470
And then I have to
add my constant.

00:06:23.470 --> 00:06:24.810
So let's come back
and just remind

00:06:24.810 --> 00:06:25.800
ourselves where we started.

00:06:25.800 --> 00:06:27.420
We started with this
trig function that

00:06:27.420 --> 00:06:29.620
was a power of tangent.

00:06:29.620 --> 00:06:33.900
And what we ultimately did is
we took two of the powers of

00:06:33.900 --> 00:06:36.550
tangent, we made a substitution
with the

00:06:36.550 --> 00:06:39.100
appropriate trigonometric
identity to make this an

00:06:39.100 --> 00:06:40.820
easier problem to solve.

00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:42.120
And actually-- yeah--

00:06:42.120 --> 00:06:44.280
if you take two of the powers
of tangent away and replace

00:06:44.280 --> 00:06:46.770
them by this, then you're always
going to end up with

00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:49.880
something of this form, tangent
to the power 2 less

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:52.080
times secant squared theta d
theta, which you can always

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:53.810
handle by a u-substitution.

00:06:53.810 --> 00:06:56.250
And you're going to end
up with an integral--

00:06:56.250 --> 00:06:57.880
now here's where it gets a
little tough-- here, you

00:06:57.880 --> 00:06:59.220
wouldn't have tangent squared.

00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:01.500
I think I might have said that
incorrectly earlier.

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:03.480
If this was any power,
here, you wouldn't

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:05.230
have tangent squared.

00:07:05.230 --> 00:07:07.300
You would have had whatever--

00:07:07.300 --> 00:07:10.820
if this was power n, this would
be power n minus 2, so

00:07:10.820 --> 00:07:12.205
this would be power n minus 2.

00:07:12.205 --> 00:07:13.550
Right?

00:07:13.550 --> 00:07:17.250
So if this was power 8, when
we do the substitution,

00:07:17.250 --> 00:07:21.120
this'll be power 6, so this
would be power 6, so this

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:22.460
would be power 6.

00:07:22.460 --> 00:07:24.080
So you'd have to do
the process again.

00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:25.370
This should remind you
of the reduction

00:07:25.370 --> 00:07:27.290
formulas you've seen.

00:07:27.290 --> 00:07:30.810
So it's good of it's even,
because if this is power 6,

00:07:30.810 --> 00:07:32.740
you do the problem again and
you end up with, the second

00:07:32.740 --> 00:07:34.260
term has a power 4.

00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:36.390
You do the problem again, the
second term has a power 2,

00:07:36.390 --> 00:07:38.060
and, oh, we know how
to deal with those.

00:07:38.060 --> 00:07:40.580
So we like it when it's
an even power.

00:07:40.580 --> 00:07:45.025
So that's kind of how these even
powers of tangent, you

00:07:45.025 --> 00:07:46.740
can take, you can find
anti-derivatives of the even

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:49.970
powers of tangent by this
strategy that winds up, you

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:53.070
could actually get a reduction
formula out of this.

00:07:53.070 --> 00:07:55.030
But I think that's where I
should stop with this problem,

00:07:55.030 --> 00:07:57.960
and I hope you enjoyed it.